$Id$

       ``The Macro Implementation of SNOBOL4 in C'' (C-MAINBOL)
		      Installation instructions

Unix systems (or systems with POSIX shell, make and m4);
=======================================================

Compilation
-----------

In most cases all you need to type is "make".

The top level makefile will run "autoconf" to create "config.m4",
which is in turn used to create Makefile2, which is then run.

Even if your system has not previously been tested (see doc/ports.doc)
autoconf may succeed. If it does not, you may want to consult
doc/porting.doc (also available as html) for information on the
available options.

For information on including "external" C functions in the linked
binary see doc/load.doc.

Installation
------------


Typing "make install" will install the snobol4 binary and man page.
The snobol4 binary and man page destnations are controlled BINDEST
(default: /usr/local/bin/snobol4) and MANDEST (default:
/usr/local/man/man1/snobol4.1) make variables, which can be overridden
by editing config.m4, or creating "local-config" (and then removing
config.m4 to trigger autoconf).

"make install" also installs the snolib.a object library, and
snolib/*.sno files to the directory named in the SNOLIB_DIR make
variable.  SNOLIB_DIR is compiled into io.o and load.o, which must be
removed if SNOLIB_DIR is changed after an xsnobol4 has been linked.

Non-unix systems;
================

None of the ports below have been tested with the latest sources.
Please send me any fixes you discover!  See doc/porting.doc for
details on porting C-MAINBOL.

The routines in tty.c (tty_save, tty_restore, tty_mode, tty_close) and
tcp.c (tcp_open) need to be supplied.  Dummy versions exist in
lib/dummy/tty.c and lib/dummy/tcp.c.

The functions referenced from pml.h will not be loaded by the existing
command files, and will cause the link to fail.  There are three
possible solutions;

1. Add commands to build a SNOLIB library and include it in the link.

2. Compile the needed objects and add them directly to the link command.

3. Define one or more of NO_PML_(HOST|EXIT|REAL|FILE|DELETE|RENAME).

The SPITBOL HOST() function simulation may call functions not
available on the target system.  Rather than adding a nest of ifdefs,
dummy versions of getenv() and system() have been provided in the
lib/dummy directory for this eventuality.  The SPITBOL EXIT()
simulation requires an execute() function to pass pass control to
another program.  A dummy version is provided in lib/dummy/execute.c.

MS-DOS using Borland C++
------------------------

Mark Emmer of Catspaw has compiled an older version of C-MAINBOL using
Borland C++.  Look in config/borland (or CONFIG\BORLAND).

VMS using DEC C
---------------

Older versions of C-MAINBOL have been run under VAX and ALPHA VMS
using DEC C, and the DEC C RTL.  config/vms/build.com is a command
file to build XSNOBOL4.EXE; config/vms/descrip.mms is an MMS description
file, which can be used by typing MMS/DESCRIP=[.CONFIG.VMS]DESCRIP.MMS.

VMS using GNU C
---------------

Jerry Lichter has run an older version of C-MAINBOL under VMS using
the GNU C compiler and the GNU C library. No command files are
available.

Anything else
-------------

C-MAINBOL has been designed to be modular, and makes only modest
demands on the C library.  See doc/porting.doc for information.

Let me know!
============

Please let me know of your success and failures to bring up C-SNOBOL4!

Please mail timing.out files to snobol4-timing@ultimate.com along with
information on your system make, model and CPU clock speed, if known.

Thanks!
-Phil


